m Bataille to Adorno, from Kant and Sade to Badiou. At the same time, he stresses Beckett’s inimitable sense of metaphysical comedy.Foregrounding Beckett’s decision to write in French, Rabaté inscribes him in a continental context marked by a “writing degree zero” while showing the prescience and ethical import of Beckett’s tendency to subvert the “human” through the theme of the animal. Beckett’s “declaration of inhuman rights,” he argues, offers the funniest mode of expression available to us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aLiterature--Philosophy. 0aTheaterxPhilosophy. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh  aAnimal Studies.  aComparative Studies of Bilingual Authors.  aethical approaches to literature.  aliterature and philosophy.  amodernism.  apost-modernism.  atheories of comedy.  atheories of the posthuman.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311072902340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823270880zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823270880423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823270880/original  a978-3-11-072902-3  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK